```javascript
function printPrimeNumbers(numbers) {
    if (numbers.length !== 5) {
        console.error('The input array must contain exactly 5 numbers.');
        return;
    }

    function isPrime(num) {
        if (num <= 1) return false;
        if (num === 2) return true;
        if (num % 2 === 0) return false;

        for (let i = 3; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i += 2) {
            if (num % i === 0) {
                return false;
            }
        }

        return true;
    }

    numbers.forEach(number => {
        if (isPrime(number)) {
            console.log(number);
        }
    });
}

// Example usage:
printPrimeNumbers([3, 5, 8, 13, 26]);
```

This function first defines an inner helper function `isPrime`, which determines whether a given number is prime. Then it iterates over the input array and prints each prime number to the console.

Remember that this function assumes that the input is an array with exactly 5 numbers. If you provide an array with more or fewer than 5 elements, it will print an error message to the console.

